</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="95E929FBA13BFF87FF18FA25FAFFCBEC" lastPageId="2" lastPageNumber="363" pageId="1" pageNumber="362" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="DD4C7A70A13BFF84FF18FA25FD63CAEB" blockId="1.[151,1437,867,2011]" pageId="1" pageNumber="362">
<emphasis id="EF87A662A13BFF84FF18FA25FE9CC9C3" bold="true" box="[199,335,1443,1470]" pageId="1" pageNumber="362">Comments.</emphasis>
<materialsCitation id="6D9B702DA13BFF84FE88FA22FD7FCAEB" ID-GBIF-Occurrence="2995036303" country="China" location="This" municipality="Northern" pageId="1" pageNumber="362" specimenCount="1" typeStatus="holotype">
<location id="D82C2CABA13BFF84FE88FA22FE5AC9C3" LSID="urn:lsid:plazi:treatment:555ACB66A13BFF87FF48FD17FAFFCBEC:D82C2CABA13BFF84FE88FA22FE5AC9C3" box="[343,393,1444,1470]" country="China" municipality="Northern" name="This" pageId="1" pageNumber="362">This</location>
new genus is known only from two male specimens from mid-elevations in 
<collectingMunicipality id="3D28E00AA13BFF84FB39FA22FA98C9C3" box="[1254,1355,1444,1470]" pageId="1" pageNumber="362">Northern</collectingMunicipality>
<collectingCountry id="A5E43AE0A13BFF84FA8DFA22FA4BC9C3" box="[1362,1432,1444,1470]" name="China" pageId="1" pageNumber="362">China</collectingCountry>
, one was collected by the author and represents the 
<typeStatus id="0248C4D2A13BFF84FD36FA4EFC98C99F" box="[745,843,1480,1506]" pageId="1" pageNumber="362">holotype</typeStatus>
specimen. The second individual that was in much better condition is known only from a series of high quality photographs taken in the field (
<figureCitation id="45C866F5A13BFF84FB48FA6AFB29CA7B" box="[1175,1274,1516,1542]" captionStart-0="FIGURE 1" captionStart-1="FIGURE 2" captionStart-2="FIGURE 3" captionStartId-0="2.[151,250,1444,1469]" captionStartId-1="3.[151,250,1002,1027]" captionStartId-2="3.[151,250,1979,2004]" captionTargetBox-0="[156,1432,489,1418]" captionTargetBox-1="[250,1336,181,977]" captionTargetBox-2="[295,1291,1085,1953]" captionTargetId-0="figure@2.[156,1432,489,1418]" captionTargetId-1="figure@3.[250,1336,181,977]" captionTargetId-2="figure@3.[295,1291,1085,1953]" captionTargetPageId-0="2" captionTargetPageId-1="3" captionTargetPageId-2="3" captionText-0="FIGURE 1. Sinothereva shangui gen. et sp. n., male, photographed in the field, Xinglong, China (Photograph copyright: Shan Gui). (Link: https://www.inaturalist.org/photos/54918804)" captionText-1="FIGURE 2. Sinothereva shangui gen. et sp. n., male, photographed in the field, Xinglong, China (Photograph copyright: Shan Gui). (Link: https://www.inaturalist.org/photos/54918833)" captionText-2="FIGURE 3. Sinothereva shangui gen. et sp. n., male, photographed in the field, Xinglong, China (Photograph copyright: Shan Gui). (Link: https://www.inaturalist.org/photos/54919032)" figureDoi-0="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3954481" figureDoi-1="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3954483" figureDoi-2="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3954485" httpUri-0="https://zenodo.org/record/3954481/files/figure.png" httpUri-1="https://zenodo.org/record/3954483/files/figure.png" httpUri-2="https://zenodo.org/record/3954485/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="362">Figs 1–3</figureCitation>
) by the nature photographer, Shan Gui. The specimen was not collected. These images were posted to iNaturalist for subsequent community-based identification. It was here through serendipity, that the author first discovered this distinctive new stiletto fly; it was subsequently compared with the previously collected specimen (but in poor condition) from the same region and confirmed as the same species
</materialsCitation>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="DD4C7A70A13BFF87FF18F926FD40CDA9" blockId="1.[151,1437,867,2011]" lastBlockId="2.[151,1437,153,468]" lastPageId="2" lastPageNumber="363" pageId="1" pageNumber="362">
This new genus and species is a member of 
<taxonomicName id="1AF301F3A13BFF84FD71F926FCFFCAC7" box="[686,812,1696,1722]" class="Insecta" family="Therevidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="362" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Therevinae">Therevinae</taxonomicName>
although it is not clear to which genus group it belongs. The most important and immediately diagnostic features of 
<taxonomicName id="1AF301F3A13BFF84FCEEF942FC65CAA3" authority="Winterton, 2020" authorityName="Winterton" authorityYear="2020" box="[817,950,1732,1758]" class="Insecta" family="Therevidae" genus="Sinothereva" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="362" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus" status="gen. n.">
<emphasis id="EF87A662A13BFF84FCEEF942FC65CAA3" box="[817,950,1732,1758]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="362">Sinothereva</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="F4B41B19A13BFF84FC63F943FBD4CAA2" box="[956,1031,1733,1759]" pageId="1" pageNumber="362" rank="genus">gen. n.</taxonomicNameLabel>
are the lack of scutellar macrosetae, the male frons much wider than the ocellar tubercle, and absence of both parafacial setae and the hind coxal knob. Also distinctive is the extensive setal pile on the entire body, including the head and femora. Some of these characteristics can also be found in 
<emphasis id="EF87A662A13BFF84FE20F8B6FD4ECB37" box="[511,669,1840,1866]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="362">
<taxonomicName id="1AF301F3A13BFF84FE20F8B6FD4ACB37" authorityName="Frey" authorityYear="1921" box="[511,665,1840,1866]" class="Insecta" family="Therevidae" genus="Aristothereva" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="362" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Aristothereva</taxonomicName>
,
</emphasis>
but 
<taxonomicName id="1AF301F3A13BFF84FD0DF8B6FC84CB37" authority="Winterton, 2020" authorityName="Winterton" authorityYear="2020" box="[722,855,1840,1866]" class="Insecta" family="Therevidae" genus="Sinothereva" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="362" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus" status="gen. n.">
<emphasis id="EF87A662A13BFF84FD0DF8B6FC84CB37" box="[722,855,1840,1866]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="362">Sinothereva</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="F4B41B19A13BFF84FC80F8B7FC7FCB36" box="[863,940,1841,1867]" pageId="1" pageNumber="362" rank="genus">gen. n.</taxonomicNameLabel>
can be differentiated by the very small and narrow arista (large and conical in 
<taxonomicName id="1AF301F3A13BFF84FDFAF8D2FD6FCB13" authorityName="Frey" authorityYear="1921" box="[549,700,1876,1902]" class="Insecta" family="Therevidae" genus="Aristothereva" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="362" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="EF87A662A13BFF84FDFAF8D2FD6FCB13" box="[549,700,1876,1902]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="362">Aristothereva</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
), lack of scutellar macrosetae (numerous in some 
<taxonomicName id="1AF301F3A13BFF84FB23F8D2FA40CB13" authorityName="Frey" authorityYear="1921" box="[1276,1427,1876,1902]" class="Insecta" family="Therevidae" genus="Aristothereva" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="362" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="EF87A662A13BFF84FB23F8D2FA40CB13" box="[1276,1427,1876,1902]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="362">Aristothereva</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) and in the male genitalia by the reduced posteriorly directed processes on the gonocoxites (well-developed in 
<taxonomicName id="1AF301F3A13BFF84FABBF8FEFED3CBCB" authorityName="Frey" authorityYear="1921" class="Insecta" family="Therevidae" genus="Aristothereva" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="362" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="EF87A662A13BFF84FABBF8FEFED3CBCB" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="362">Aristothereva</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
). Indeed, 
<taxonomicName id="1AF301F3A13BFF84FEACF81AFE2BCBCB" authorityName="Winterton" authorityYear="2020" box="[371,504,1948,1974]" class="Insecta" family="Therevidae" genus="Sinothereva" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="362" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="EF87A662A13BFF84FEACF81AFE2BCBCB" box="[371,504,1948,1974]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="362">Sinothereva</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
shows considerable affinity for 
<taxonomicName id="1AF301F3A13BFF84FCBBF81AFC28CBCB" authorityName="Frey" authorityYear="1921" box="[868,1019,1948,1974]" class="Insecta" family="Therevidae" genus="Aristothereva" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="362" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="EF87A662A13BFF84FCBBF81AFC28CBCB" box="[868,1019,1948,1974]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="362">Aristothereva</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and these two Palaearctic genera are likely closely related. Broader relationships of 
<taxonomicName id="1AF301F3A13BFF84FD6CF846FCEBCBA7" authority="Winterton, 2020" authorityName="Winterton" authorityYear="2020" box="[691,824,1984,2010]" class="Insecta" family="Therevidae" genus="Sinothereva" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="362" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus" status="gen. n.">
<emphasis id="EF87A662A13BFF84FD6CF846FCEBCBA7" box="[691,824,1984,2010]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="362">Sinothereva</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="F4B41B19A13BFF84FC9EF847FC5CCBA6" box="[833,911,1985,2011]" pageId="1" pageNumber="362" rank="genus">gen. n.</taxonomicNameLabel>
(and 
<taxonomicName id="1AF301F3A13BFF84FC0BF846FBB8CBA7" authorityName="Frey" authorityYear="1921" box="[980,1131,1984,2010]" class="Insecta" family="Therevidae" genus="Aristothereva" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="362" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="EF87A662A13BFF84FC0BF846FBB8CBA7" box="[980,1131,1984,2010]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="362">Aristothereva</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) to other therevine genera are less clear. Morphological synapomorphies uniting members of either the 
<taxonomicName id="1AF301F3A138FF87FC28FF1FFB81CCCE" authorityName="Latreille" authorityYear="1796" box="[1015,1106,153,179]" class="Insecta" family="Therevidae" genus="Thereva" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="363" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="EF87A662A138FF87FC28FF1FFB81CCCE" box="[1015,1106,153,179]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="363">Thereva</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
or 
<taxonomicName id="1AF301F3A138FF87FBA7FF1FFB2CCCCE" authorityName="Irwin &amp; Lyneborg" authorityYear="1981" box="[1144,1279,153,179]" class="Insecta" family="Therevidae" genus="Pandivirilia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="363" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="EF87A662A138FF87FBA7FF1FFB2CCCCE" box="[1144,1279,153,179]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="363">Pandivirilia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
genus groups are not well defined (see 
<bibRefCitation id="B9620781A138FF87FE65FF3BFD4CCCAA" author="Holston, K. C. &amp; Irwin, M. E. &amp; Wiegmann, B. M." box="[442,671,189,215]" pageId="2" pageNumber="363" pagination="279 - 296" refId="ref3144" refString="Holston, K. C., Irwin, M. E. &amp; Wiegmann, B. M. (2007) Monophyly and phylogenetic relationships of Thereva and therevine genus-groups (Insecta: Diptera: Therevidae) based on EF- 1 α, 28 S rDNA and mitochondrial 16 S rDNA sequences. Invertebrate Systematics, 21, 279 - 296." type="journal article" year="2007">
Holston 
<emphasis id="EF87A662A138FF87FDC4FF38FD9DCCAA" box="[539,590,189,215]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="363">et al</emphasis>
., 2007
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="B9620781A138FF87FD73FF3BFC78CCA5" author="Winterton, S. L. &amp; Hardy, N. B. &amp; Gaimari, S. D. &amp; Hauser, M. &amp; Hill, H. N. &amp; Holston, K. C. &amp; Irwin, M. E. &amp; Lambkin, C. L. &amp; Metz, M. A. &amp; Turco, F. &amp; Webb, D. &amp; Yang, L. &amp; Yeates, D. K. &amp; Wiegmann, B. M." box="[684,939,189,216]" pageId="2" pageNumber="363" pagination="144 - 161" refId="ref3440" refString="Winterton, S. L., Hardy, N. B., Gaimari, S. D., Hauser, M., Hill, H. N., Holston, K. C., Irwin, M. E., Lambkin, C. L., Metz, M. A., Turco, F., Webb, D., Yang, L., Yeates, D. K. &amp; Wiegmann, B. M. (2016) The phylogeny of stiletto flies (Diptera: Therevidae). Systematic Entomology, 41, 144 - 161." type="journal article" year="2016">
Winterton 
<emphasis id="EF87A662A138FF87FCFAFF38FC8BCCAA" box="[805,856,189,215]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="363">et al</emphasis>
., 2016
</bibRefCitation>
), and 
<taxonomicName id="1AF301F3A138FF87FC2EFF3BFBA5CCAA" authority="Winterton, 2020" authorityName="Winterton" authorityYear="2020" box="[1009,1142,189,215]" class="Insecta" family="Therevidae" genus="Sinothereva" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="363" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus" status="gen. n.">
<emphasis id="EF87A662A138FF87FC2EFF3BFBA5CCAA" box="[1009,1142,189,215]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="363">Sinothereva</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="F4B41B19A138FF87FBA1FF3BFB18CCAA" box="[1150,1227,189,215]" pageId="2" pageNumber="363" rank="genus">gen. n.</taxonomicNameLabel>
and 
<taxonomicName id="1AF301F3A138FF87FADAFF3BFA4FCCAA" authorityName="Frey" authorityYear="1921" box="[1285,1436,189,215]" class="Insecta" family="Therevidae" genus="Aristothereva" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="363" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="EF87A662A138FF87FADAFF3BFA4FCCAA" box="[1285,1436,189,215]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="363">Aristothereva</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
exhibit characteristics of both. 
<taxonomicName id="1AF301F3A138FF87FE2DFF67FCD3CC86" authority="Lyneborg" authorityName="Lyneborg" authorityYear="1978" box="[498,768,225,251]" class="Insecta" family="Therevidae" genus="Neotherevella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="363" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="EF87A662A138FF87FE2DFF67FD5DCC86" box="[498,654,225,251]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="363">Neotherevella</emphasis>
Lyneborg
</taxonomicName>
appears to be related to 
<taxonomicName id="1AF301F3A138FF87FBCCFF67FB79CC86" authorityName="Frey" authorityYear="1921" box="[1043,1194,225,251]" class="Insecta" family="Therevidae" genus="Aristothereva" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="363" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="EF87A662A138FF87FBCCFF67FB79CC86" box="[1043,1194,225,251]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="363">Aristothereva</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="1AF301F3A138FF87FB3EFF67FAB5CC86" authority="Winterton, 2020" authorityName="Winterton" authorityYear="2020" box="[1249,1382,225,251]" class="Insecta" family="Therevidae" genus="Sinothereva" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="363" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus" status="gen. n.">
<emphasis id="EF87A662A138FF87FB3EFF67FAB5CC86" box="[1249,1382,225,251]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="363">Sinothereva</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="F4B41B19A138FF87FAB2FF67FF7FCD62" pageId="2" pageNumber="363" rank="genus">gen. n.</taxonomicNameLabel>
and is found in the Palaearctic and Afrotropical regions. 
<taxonomicName id="1AF301F3A138FF87FCF2FE83FC1ACD62" authorityName="Lyneborg" authorityYear="1978" box="[813,969,261,287]" class="Insecta" family="Therevidae" genus="Neotherevella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="363" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="EF87A662A138FF87FCF2FE83FC1ACD62" box="[813,969,261,287]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="363">Neotherevella</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has a similar habitus with extensive erect whitish to silvery setal pile, male frons usually wider than the ocellar tubercle and parafacial setae absent, amongst other features. In contrast with 
<taxonomicName id="1AF301F3A138FF87FE2DFECBFDA4CD1A" authority="Winterton, 2020" authorityName="Winterton" authorityYear="2020" box="[498,631,333,359]" class="Insecta" family="Therevidae" genus="Sinothereva" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="363" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus" status="gen. n.">
<emphasis id="EF87A662A138FF87FE2DFECBFDA4CD1A" box="[498,631,333,359]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="363">Sinothereva</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="F4B41B19A138FF87FDA1FECBFD19CD1A" box="[638,714,333,359]" pageId="2" pageNumber="363" rank="genus">gen. n.</taxonomicNameLabel>
, both 
<taxonomicName id="1AF301F3A138FF87FCD1FECBFC79CD1A" authorityName="Lyneborg" authorityYear="1978" box="[782,938,333,359]" class="Insecta" family="Therevidae" genus="Neotherevella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="363" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="EF87A662A138FF87FCD1FECBFC79CD1A" box="[782,938,333,359]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="363">Neotherevella</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="1AF301F3A138FF87FC3FFECBFBA4CD1A" authorityName="Frey" authorityYear="1921" box="[992,1143,333,359]" class="Insecta" family="Therevidae" genus="Aristothereva" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="363" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="EF87A662A138FF87FC3FFECBFBA4CD1A" box="[992,1143,333,359]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="363">Aristothereva</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
have scutellar macrosetae present. 
<bibRefCitation id="B9620781A138FF87FF28FEF7FE30CDF6" author="Holston, K. C. &amp; Irwin, M. E. &amp; Wiegmann, B. M." box="[247,483,369,395]" pageId="2" pageNumber="363" pagination="279 - 296" refId="ref3144" refString="Holston, K. C., Irwin, M. E. &amp; Wiegmann, B. M. (2007) Monophyly and phylogenetic relationships of Thereva and therevine genus-groups (Insecta: Diptera: Therevidae) based on EF- 1 α, 28 S rDNA and mitochondrial 16 S rDNA sequences. Invertebrate Systematics, 21, 279 - 296." type="journal article" year="2007">
Holston 
<emphasis id="EF87A662A138FF87FE87FEF4FE59CDF6" box="[344,394,369,395]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="363">et al</emphasis>
. (2007)
</bibRefCitation>
considered 
<taxonomicName id="1AF301F3A138FF87FDB3FEF7FCD0CDF6" authorityName="Frey" authorityYear="1921" box="[620,771,369,395]" class="Insecta" family="Therevidae" genus="Aristothereva" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="363" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="EF87A662A138FF87FDB3FEF7FCD0CDF6" box="[620,771,369,395]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="363">Aristothereva</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="1AF301F3A138FF87FCE3FEF7FC0BCDF6" authorityName="Lyneborg" authorityYear="1978" box="[828,984,369,395]" class="Insecta" family="Therevidae" genus="Neotherevella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="363" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="EF87A662A138FF87FCE3FEF7FC0BCDF6" box="[828,984,369,395]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="363">Neotherevella</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as part of the 
<taxonomicName id="1AF301F3A138FF87FBA4FEF7FAD1CDF6" authorityName="Irwin &amp; Lyneborg" authorityYear="1981" box="[1147,1282,369,395]" class="Insecta" family="Therevidae" genus="Pandivirilia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="363" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="EF87A662A138FF87FBA4FEF7FAD1CDF6" box="[1147,1282,369,395]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="363">Pandivirilia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
genus group, although these genera were not sampled in any of the published phylogenetic analyses to confirm this hypothesis (
<bibRefCitation id="B9620781A138FF87FF7EFE3FFE52CDAE" author="Holston, K. C. &amp; Irwin, M. E. &amp; Wiegmann, B. M." box="[161,385,441,467]" pageId="2" pageNumber="363" pagination="279 - 296" refId="ref3144" refString="Holston, K. C., Irwin, M. E. &amp; Wiegmann, B. M. (2007) Monophyly and phylogenetic relationships of Thereva and therevine genus-groups (Insecta: Diptera: Therevidae) based on EF- 1 α, 28 S rDNA and mitochondrial 16 S rDNA sequences. Invertebrate Systematics, 21, 279 - 296." type="journal article" year="2007">
Holston 
<emphasis id="EF87A662A138FF87FEDFFE3CFEE2CDAE" box="[256,305,441,467]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="363">et al</emphasis>
., 2007
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="B9620781A138FF87FE53FE3FFD54CDA9" author="Winterton, S. L. &amp; Hardy, N. B. &amp; Gaimari, S. D. &amp; Hauser, M. &amp; Hill, H. N. &amp; Holston, K. C. &amp; Irwin, M. E. &amp; Lambkin, C. L. &amp; Metz, M. A. &amp; Turco, F. &amp; Webb, D. &amp; Yang, L. &amp; Yeates, D. K. &amp; Wiegmann, B. M." box="[396,647,441,468]" pageId="2" pageNumber="363" pagination="144 - 161" refId="ref3440" refString="Winterton, S. L., Hardy, N. B., Gaimari, S. D., Hauser, M., Hill, H. N., Holston, K. C., Irwin, M. E., Lambkin, C. L., Metz, M. A., Turco, F., Webb, D., Yang, L., Yeates, D. K. &amp; Wiegmann, B. M. (2016) The phylogeny of stiletto flies (Diptera: Therevidae). Systematic Entomology, 41, 144 - 161." type="journal article" year="2016">
Winterton 
<emphasis id="EF87A662A138FF87FDDBFE3CFDE6CDAE" box="[516,565,441,467]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="363">et al</emphasis>
., 2016
</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<caption id="898C2AF8A138FF87FF48FA22FD35C99D" ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3954481" ID-Zenodo-Dep="3954481" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3954481/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="363" startId="2.[151,250,1444,1469]" targetBox="[156,1432,489,1418]" targetPageId="2">
